The {{nihongo|'''Casio Loopy'''|ルーピー|Rūpī|lead=yes}}, subtitled ''My Seal Computer SV-100'', is a [[32-bit]] [[home video game console]]. Released exclusively in [[Video gaming in Japan|Japan]] in October 1995,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uk.playright.dk/raretitel.php?id=29220|title=Play:Right Rare > Hardware > Casio Loopy|accessdate=2008-07-10}}</ref> it was unique in that the marketing for it was completely targeted to [[Women and video games|female gamers]].

The Loopy includes a built-in thermal color [[Computer printer|printer]] that can be used to create [[sticker]]s from game screenshots. An optional accessory, called {{nihongo|''Magical Shop''|マジカルショップ|Majikaru Shoppu}}, is a video capture device to obtain images from [[Videocassette recorder|VCRs]] and [[DVD player]]s. Users may add text to these images and make stickers. Including Magical Shop's own built-in software, the Loopy game library contains 11 titles. The Loopy features one controller port for use with a standard [[game controller]] or with a mouse (sold separately). Developer [[Kenji Terada]] worked on ''Loopy Town no Oheya ga Hoshii!''.

Casio dropped the support of the console in 1996, only one year after its release.

