{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}} {{Infobox person | name = Ludmila Zeman | birth_name = Ludmila Zemanová | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1947|04|23}} | birth_place = [[Zlín]], Moravia, [[Czechoslovakia]] | residence = [[Montreal|Montreal, Quebec]], Canada | nationality = [[Czech Canadians|Czech-Canadian]] | education = Střední uměleckoprůmyslová škola, [[Uherské Hradiště]] | alma_mater = | occupation = Artist, animator | years_active = | known_for = Children's books and animated films | notable_works = | spouse = Eugen Spálený | children = {{ubl|Linda Zeman-Spaleny|Malvina Spaleny}} | parents = [[Karel Zeman]] | awards = [[1995 Governor General's Awards|1995 Governor General's Award for Children's Illustration]] | website = {{URL|LudmilaZeman.com}} }}
'''Ludmila Zeman''' (born 23 April 1947) is a [[Czech Canadians|Czech–Canadian]] artist, animator, and creator of [[children's book]]s. She is the daughter of filmmaker [[Karel Zeman]].<ref name="library">{{cite web |url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/read-up-on-it/015020-6061-e.html |title=Archived Content: Ludmila Zeman |publisher=[[Library and Archives Canada]] |date=2002-09-25<!--date modified--> |accessdate=2013-02-07}}</ref><ref name="embassy">{{cite web |url=http://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/japan-japon/events-evenements/gallery-20110525-galerie.aspx?view=d |title=Children's Story Books and Animations by Ludmila Zeman: June 14 – July 22, 2011: Embassy of Canada Prince Takamado Gallery |publisher=[[Government of Canada]] (canadainternational.gc.ca) |date=2012-06-04<!--date modified--> |accessdate=2013-02-07}}</ref><ref name="tundra">{{cite web |url=http://www.tundrabooks.com/authors/Zeman_l.html |title=Tundra Books Online: Ludmila Zeman|publisher=[[Tundra Books]] (tundrabooks.com) |date=|accessdate=2013-02-07}}</ref>
Zeman was born in the Moravian Czech city of [[Zlín]] (renamed Gottwaldov in 1949, through 1989).<ref name=library/><!-- ref source gives Gottwaldov; source for explanation is our linked article --> She graduated from the college of art (Střední uměleckoprůmyslová škola) in [[Uherské Hradiště]].<ref name=Storymakers>{{cite book |author=[[Canadian Children's Book Centre]] |title=The Storymakers: Illustrating Children's Books: 72 Artists and Illustrators Talk About Their Work|location=Markham, Ontario|publisher=Pembroke Publishers|year=1999|pages=150–51 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6kkJ7RXwdqMC&pg=PA150 |accessdate=2013-08-21}}</ref> She worked as her father's assistant for his final films, and married Eugen Spálený, the chief animator at his studio. They had two children, Linda and Malvinia.<ref name=Grutz/> She launched a career in story books and animation for children.<ref name="embassy"/>
In 1983, Zeman and her husband were invited to teach [[film technique]] at [[Emily Carr University of Art and Design]] in Vancouver. When the couple attempted to emigrate, the Czechoslovakian communist government refused them permission, accusing them of pro-Western leanings. Zeman was told to leave the animation studio, and Spálený was drafted into menial construction work. In the summer of 1984, the family escaped through [[Yugoslavia]] to a refugee camp in [[Austria]], finally arriving in Canada to accept the teaching posts.<ref name=Grutz/>
''The Cedar Tree of Life'', a thirty-second animated segment the couple produced for the Canadian edition of ''[[Sesame Street]]'', attracted the attention of the [[National Film Board of Canada]], which invited the couple to make a short film on a topic of their choice.<ref name=Grutz/> Zeman's production was ''Lord of the Sky'', based on myths of the [[aboriginal peoples in Canada|Canadian north Pacific First Nations]]<ref name="embassy"/> and produced using [[cutout animation|paper cutouts]]. The film was a success, winning eleven international awards, including a blue ribbon at the [[American Film Festival]] in 1993; it was shown at the [[Sundance Film Festival]] the following year and was shortlisted for an [[Academy Award]] nomination.<ref name=Grutz/>
Following ''Lord of the Sky'', Zeman and Spálený planned a feature-length animated film based on the ''[[Epic of Gilgamesh]]''. Karel Zeman had introduced the epic, which was among his favorite books, to Ludmila when she was eleven.<ref name=Grutz/> The concept was eventually developed into a trilogy of children's books written and illustrated by Zeman: ''Gilgamesh the King'' (1991), ''The Revenge of Ishtar'' (1993), and ''The Last Quest of Gilgamesh'' (1995).<ref name=Grutz>{{cite journal |title=Zeman's Gilgamesh |last=Grutz|first=Jane Waldron |journal=[[Saudi Aramco World]] |date=May–June 1996|pages=18–26 |url=http://archive.aramcoworld.com/issue/199603/zeman.s.gilgamesh.htm |accessdate=2018-07-22}}</ref> The final book in the trilogy won the [[1995 Governor General's Awards|1995 Governor General's Award for Children's Illustration]].<ref name=gg>{{cite web |title=1995 Winners|url=http://ggbooks.canadacouncil.ca/en/about-apropos/archives/1995/Winners.aspx |work=[[Governor General's Awards]] |publisher=[[Canada Council for the Arts]] (canadacouncil.ca) |accessdate=2013-05-20}}</ref> The [[Embassy of Canada]] in Japan presented an exhibition of Ludmila Zeman's work in Tokyo in 2011.<ref name="embassy"/>
